    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-04-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-04-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="638"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d638">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/2615½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-04-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">7 April, 1916</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Thank you for letting me see
                    the enclosed.<note n="22" xml:id="d638fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_680">p. 680</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>It is probably too late now to answer Gerard’s question about the advisability of
                    sending a special representative of the German Government here (a “German
                    Colonel House”), but if there should be a renewal of the suggestion or Gerard
                    should for any reason remind us of it I think we should say that we would of
                    course welcome any messenger of friendly counsel the Emperor might think it
                    desirable to send,—without indicating any judgment or desire of our own about
                    the matter.</p>
                <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>W. W.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
